> So - for enrichment purposes (enriched leaves generation) we want to stick with is_a and part_of, but for anchors (themes) regulates would be fine because it groups related parts of the same story.


This is a really clean insight and it's architecturally sound. Let me work through the implications.

Why the split makes sense
Leaves (is_a + part_of only — keep as-is):
Leaves represent the most specific enriched terms in the ontological hierarchy. The leaf computation is asking "what is the finest-grained biological specificity present in this data?" regulates shouldn't participate here because "regulation of leukocyte migration" is not a more specific kind of "leukocyte migration" — it's a control relationship. Including it would blur what the leaf layer means.

Anchors (is_a + part_of + regulates):
The anchor layer is asking "what is the best grouping node for telling a coherent biological story?" Here regulates is exactly right, because:

"leukocyte migration" + "regulation of leukocyte migration" + "positive regulation of leukocyte migration" are all facets of the same biological story
The process term becomes the natural anchor; the regulatory variants become its specific sub-themes
This is precisely what an explanation consumer wants: "these genes drive leukocyte migration, and these genes modulate that migration"
What changes in the code
In go_hierarchy.py, get_all_descendants already has an explicit reverse-scan for part_of:


# Check part_of reverse relationships
for term_id, dag_term in godag.items():
    if hasattr(dag_term, "relationship") and dag_term.relationship:
        for rel_type, rel_terms in dag_term.relationship.items():
            if rel_type == "part_of":   # ← extend to regulates here
Extending this to also collect regulates, positively_regulates, and negatively_regulates is the minimal change. The process anchor (e.g., "leukocyte migration") would then absorb all enriched terms that declare they regulate it.

One subtlety to resolve
The assignment priority in build_depth_anchor_themes currently prefers the more specific anchor (higher depth). With regulates added, there's a new conflict: "positive regulation of leukocyte migration" is both:

An is_a child of "regulation of leukocyte migration" (so it might be absorbed there)
A regulates child of "leukocyte migration" (so it might be absorbed there)
The resolution that produces the most useful narratives is probably: is_a/part_of grouping takes priority over regulates grouping. So "positive regulation" stays under "regulation of leukocyte migration" if that anchor exists — but the whole "regulation of leukocyte migration" subtree then gets absorbed under "leukocyte migration" as a regulates-linked child. This gives a two-level structure:


Theme: leukocyte migration
  ├── [is_a] myeloid leukocyte migration
  ├── [is_a] mononuclear cell migration  
  ├── [is_a] dendritic cell migration
  ├── [regulates] regulation of leukocyte migration
  │     ├── [is_a] positive regulation of leukocyte migration
  │     └── [is_a] regulation of neutrophil migration
  └── [regulates] negative regulation of leukocyte migration
That's 3-4 current themes → 1 coherent theme, without losing the regulatory narrative. Worth a Ring 2 experiment once you've validated the simpler fixes first.